<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,726,1257]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,798,824]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[717,861,799,825]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="El-Hawagry, M. S. &amp; Abdel-Dayem, M. S. &amp; Elgharbawy, A. A. &amp; Al Dhafer, H. M." box="[902,1185,799,826]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="107 - 139" refId="ref32055" refString="El-Hawagry, M. S., Abdel-Dayem, M. S., Elgharbawy, A. A. &amp; Al Dhafer, H. M. (2016) A preliminary account of the fly fauna in Jabal Shada al-A'la Nature Reserve, Saudi Arabia, with new records and biogeographical remarks (Diptera, Insecta). Zookeys, 636, 107 - 139. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 636.9905" type="journal article" year="2016">
El-Hawagry 
<emphasis box="[1045,1094,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. (2016)
</bibRefCitation>
. It was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,243,835,861]" name="Sweden" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Sweden</collectingCountry>
. In the Middle East it was recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[707,787,835,861]" name="Turkey" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C. &amp; Werner, D. &amp; Kachvoryan, E. A." box="[802,986,834,861]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="73 - 86" refId="ref35115" refString="Pont, A. C., Werner, D. &amp; Kachvoryan, E. A. (2005) A preliminary list of the Fannidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of Armenia. Zoology in the Middle East, 36 (1), 73 - 86. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 09397140.2005.10638130" type="journal article" year="2005">
Pont 
<emphasis box="[862,911,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2005
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,726,1257]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,444,870,897]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
This species is closely related to the house fly but is slightly larger, it is 
<quantity box="[1242,1334,871,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7â€“8 mm</quantity>
long and grey in colour with four dark stripes on the thorax, and a grey-black patterned abdomen (
<bibRefCitation author="Gregor, F. &amp; Rozkosny, R. &amp; Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J." box="[1146,1358,907,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 280" refId="ref32614" refString="Gregor, F., Rozkosny, R., Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J. (2002) The Muscidae (Diptera) of Central Europe. Folia Facultatis Scientiarum Naturalium, Universitatis Masarykianae Brunensis, Biologia, 107, 1 - 280." type="journal article" year="2002">
Gregor 
<emphasis box="[1234,1283,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,726,1257]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,942,969]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Biological remarks.</emphasis>
It is a non-biting fly. The larvae feed on manure juices and plant sugars. Adults feed during the day on secretions around the eyes, mouth and nostrils on cattle and horses (
<bibRefCitation author="Gregor, F. &amp; Rozkosny, R. &amp; Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J." box="[1035,1247,979,1005]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 280" refId="ref32614" refString="Gregor, F., Rozkosny, R., Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J. (2002) The Muscidae (Diptera) of Central Europe. Folia Facultatis Scientiarum Naturalium, Universitatis Masarykianae Brunensis, Biologia, 107, 1 - 280." type="journal article" year="2002">
Gregor 
<emphasis box="[1123,1172,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
). It is considered a pest species, as it transmits eyeworm 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bosc" authorityYear="1819" box="[584,680,1015,1041]" class="Chromadorea" family="Thelaziidae" genus="Thelazia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[584,680,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Thelazia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (
<taxonomicName box="[746,856,1015,1041]" class="Chromadorea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Nematoda" rank="order">Spirurida</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[865,997,1015,1042]" class="Secernentea" family="Thelaziidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Nematoda" rank="family">Thelaziidae</taxonomicName>
) to cattle and horses, and pinkeye (conjunctivitis) in cattle. The latter is an infection of the surface of the eye by the bacteria 
<taxonomicName box="[1106,1288,1051,1077]" class="Gammaproteobacteria" family="Moraxellaceae" genus="Moraxella" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Pseudomonadales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Proteobacteria" rank="species" species="bovis">
<emphasis box="[1106,1288,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Moraxella bovis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a result of irritants by pollen grain or dust scratching the cornea of the eye which increases the secretion of tears from the eye. This then attracts 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Geer" authorityYear="1776" box="[347,507,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="autumnalis">
<emphasis box="[347,507,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">M. autumnalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to feed on the tears, which spreads 
<taxonomicName box="[898,993,1123,1149]" class="Gammaproteobacteria" family="Moraxellaceae" genus="Moraxella" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Pseudomonadales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Proteobacteria" rank="species" species="bovis">
<emphasis box="[898,993,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">M. bovis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that causes pinkeye in cattle (
<bibRefCitation author="Krafsur, E. S. &amp; Moon, R. D." pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="503 - 523" refId="ref33403" refString="Krafsur, E. S. &amp; Moon, R. D. (1997) Bionomics of the face fly, Musca autumnalis. Annual Review of Entomology, 42, 503 - 523. https: // doi. org / 10.1146 / annurev. ento. 42.1.503" type="journal article" year="1997">Krafsur &amp; Moon 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Giangaspero, A. &amp; Traversa, D. &amp; Otranto, D." box="[296,567,1159,1185]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="257 - 259" refId="ref32457" refString="Giangaspero, A., Traversa, D. &amp; Otranto, D. (2004) Ecology of Thelazia spp. in cattle and their vectors in Italy. Parasitologia, 46 (1 - 2), 257 - 259." type="journal article" year="2004">
Giangaspero 
<emphasis box="[444,501,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C. &amp; Werner, D. &amp; Kachvoryan, E. A." box="[578,760,1158,1185]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="73 - 86" refId="ref35115" refString="Pont, A. C., Werner, D. &amp; Kachvoryan, E. A. (2005) A preliminary list of the Fannidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of Armenia. Zoology in the Middle East, 36 (1), 73 - 86. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 09397140.2005.10638130" type="journal article" year="2005">
Pont 
<emphasis box="[636,685,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2005
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Bradbury, R. S. &amp; Breen, K. &amp; Bonura, E. M. &amp; Hoyt, J. W. &amp; Bishop, H. S." box="[778,1029,1159,1185]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1171 - 1174" refId="ref30392" refString="Bradbury, R. S., Breen, K. v., Bonura, E. M., Hoyt, J. W. &amp; Bishop, H. S. (2018) case report: conjunctival infestation with Thelaziz gulosa: A novel agent of human Thelaziasis in the United States. The American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene, 98 (4), 1171 - 1174. https: // doi. org / 10.4269 / ajtmh. 17 - 0870" type="journal article" year="2018">
Bradbury 
<emphasis box="[891,947,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(2018)
</bibRefCitation>
reported a case of Thelaziasis in the eye of a 26 year old women where 14 worms of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Railliet &amp; Henry)" baseAuthorityName="Railliet &amp; Henry" box="[699,1018,1195,1221]" class="Chromadorea" family="Thelaziidae" genus="Thelazia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Nematoda" rank="species" species="gulosa">
<emphasis box="[699,802,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">T. gulosa</emphasis>
(Railliet &amp; Henry)
</taxonomicName>
were found to have been transmitted by this species. There is a record that this species has also caused myiasis in cattle (
<bibRefCitation author="Gilarriortua, M." box="[1084,1286,1230,1257]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="312 - 316" refId="ref32500" refString="Gilarriortua, M. (2015) First record of Musca autumnalis De Geer, 1776 (Dipera: Muscidae) species involved in a myiasis case in the Basque country cattle (Iberian Peninsula). Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa, 55, 312 - 316." type="journal article" year="2015">Gilarriortua 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
